bead.description:
Share a canonical manifest of AuthError variants between Rust (axon-core) and the TypeScript SDK. Parity is enforced by tests in BOTH languages — no heavy codegen, just a JSON manifest and a parity guard.

## Important context — the count is 15, not 14

B4 added `GrantsExceedRole` as the 15th AuthError variant. The bead was drafted before B4. When you write the manifest, include all 15 variants and reference AUTH_ERROR_VARIANT_COUNT = 15.

## Scope

### 1. Create the manifest: schema/auth-errors.manifest.json (workspace root)

A single JSON file at the workspace root that is the source of truth:

    {
      "$schema": "https://axon.dev/schemas/auth-errors-manifest.v1.json",
      "version": 1,
      "variants": [
        { "rust_name": "Unauthenticated",      "code": "unauthenticated",          "status": 401 },
        { "rust_name": "CredentialMalformed",  "code": "credential_malformed",     "status": 401 },
        { "rust_name": "CredentialInvalid",    "code": "credential_invalid",       "status": 401 },
        { "rust_name": "CredentialExpired",    "code": "credential_expired",       "status": 401 },
        { "rust_name": "CredentialNotYetValid","code": "credential_not_yet_valid", "status": 401 },
        { "rust_name": "CredentialRevoked",    "code": "credential_revoked",       "status": 401 },
        { "rust_name": "CredentialForeignIssuer","code": "credential_foreign_issuer","status": 401 },
        { "rust_name": "CredentialWrongTenant","code": "credential_wrong_tenant",  "status": 403 },
        { "rust_name": "UserSuspended",        "code": "user_suspended",           "status": 401 },
        { "rust_name": "NotATenantMember",     "code": "not_a_tenant_member",      "status": 403 },
        { "rust_name": "DatabaseNotGranted",   "code": "database_not_granted",     "status": 403 },
        { "rust_name": "OpNotGranted",         "code": "op_not_granted",           "status": 403 },
        { "rust_name": "GrantsExceedRole",     "code": "grants_exceed_role",       "status": 403 }
      ]
    }

**Verify against the current Rust source before writing the manifest** — the variant list above is my best guess but the source of truth is crates/axon-core/src/auth.rs. Read it first, then build the manifest from what's actually there. If any variant names or codes differ, go with what the source says.

Note: count the variants. AUTH_ERROR_VARIANT_COUNT should equal the manifest's variants.length. Currently expected: 15. If the Rust source has more or fewer, reconcile before proceeding.

### 2. Rust parity test: crates/axon-core/tests/auth_error_manifest_test.rs (NEW)

    //! Parity test: every AuthError variant must have a row in
    //! schema/auth-errors.manifest.json with the correct (status, code).

    use axon_core::auth::AuthError;

    #[test]
    fn manifest_matches_rust_variants() {
        // Read the manifest from the workspace root.
        let manifest_path = std::path::Path::new(env!("CARGO_MANIFEST_DIR"))
            .parent()  // crates
            .unwrap()
            .parent()  // workspace root
            .unwrap()
            .join("schema/auth-errors.manifest.json");

        let raw = std::fs::read_to_string(&manifest_path)
            .expect("read manifest");
        let json: serde_json::Value = serde_json::from_str(&raw).unwrap();
        let variants = json["variants"].as_array().unwrap();

        // Walk every variant in the manifest, construct the corresponding
        // AuthError (using a helper or a match on the rust_name string),
        // and assert its status_code() and error_code() match the manifest.
        for v in variants {
            let rust_name = v["rust_name"].as_str().unwrap();
            let expected_code = v["code"].as_str().unwrap();
            let expected_status = v["status"].as_u64().unwrap() as u16;

            let err = auth_error_by_name(rust_name);
            assert_eq!(err.error_code(), expected_code, "code mismatch for {rust_name}");
            assert_eq!(err.status_code(), expected_status, "status mismatch for {rust_name}");
        }

        // Also assert the count matches AUTH_ERROR_VARIANT_COUNT.
        assert_eq!(variants.len(), axon_core::auth::AUTH_ERROR_VARIANT_COUNT);
    }

    fn auth_error_by_name(name: &str) -> AuthError {
        match name {
            "Unauthenticated" => AuthError::Unauthenticated,
            "CredentialMalformed" => AuthError::CredentialMalformed,
            // ... one arm per variant ...
            _ => panic!("unknown AuthError variant: {name}"),
        }
    }

The `auth_error_by_name` helper enumerates every variant explicitly — this is a compile-time check because Rust's exhaustiveness rules will fail the test if a new variant is added without updating the helper (or the test assertion will panic at runtime, which is acceptable for a parity test).

### 3. TS SDK error enum: sdk/typescript/src/auth-error-codes.ts (NEW)

    /**
     * AUTO-MAINTAINED: mirror of schema/auth-errors.manifest.json
     *
     * If you edit this file, also edit the manifest. The parity test in
     * test/auth-error-manifest.test.ts will fail if the two drift.
     */

    export const AUTH_ERROR_CODES = [
      "unauthenticated",
      "credential_malformed",
      "credential_invalid",
      "credential_expired",
      "credential_not_yet_valid",
      "credential_revoked",
      "credential_foreign_issuer",
      "credential_wrong_tenant",
      "user_suspended",
      "not_a_tenant_member",
      "database_not_granted",
      "op_not_granted",
      "grants_exceed_role",
    ] as const;

    export type AuthErrorCode = (typeof AUTH_ERROR_CODES)[number];

    /** HTTP status by error code (matches ADR-018 §4 + GrantsExceedRole at 403). */
    export const AUTH_ERROR_STATUS: Record<AuthErrorCode, 401 | 403> = {
      unauthenticated: 401,
      credential_malformed: 401,
      credential_invalid: 401,
      credential_expired: 401,
      credential_not_yet_valid: 401,
      credential_revoked: 401,
      credential_foreign_issuer: 401,
      credential_wrong_tenant: 403,
      user_suspended: 401,
      not_a_tenant_member: 403,
      database_not_granted: 403,
      op_not_granted: 403,
      grants_exceed_role: 403,
    };

    export const AUTH_ERROR_COUNT = AUTH_ERROR_CODES.length; // 13 (no, 15 — verify against Rust source)

Verify the count matches the Rust source. The mismatch here (13 vs 15) is because I can't currently read the manifest from the draft. Use whatever the Rust source says.

### 4. TS SDK parity test: sdk/typescript/test/auth-error-manifest.test.ts (NEW)

    import { describe, it, expect } from "vitest";
    import * as fs from "node:fs";
    import * as path from "node:path";
    import {
      AUTH_ERROR_CODES,
      AUTH_ERROR_STATUS,
      AUTH_ERROR_COUNT,
    } from "../src/auth-error-codes.js";

    describe("auth error manifest parity", () => {
      it("matches the canonical manifest", () => {
        const manifestPath = path.resolve(__dirname, "../../../schema/auth-errors.manifest.json");
        const raw = fs.readFileSync(manifestPath, "utf8");
        const json = JSON.parse(raw);
        expect(json.variants.length).toBe(AUTH_ERROR_COUNT);

        for (const v of json.variants) {
          expect(AUTH_ERROR_CODES).toContain(v.code);
          expect(AUTH_ERROR_STATUS[v.code as any]).toBe(v.status);
        }
      });
    });

### 5. Wire AuthErrorCode into the HttpAxonClient

In sdk/typescript/src/http-client.ts, update AxonHttpError to use the AuthErrorCode type (or a looser string fallback):

    import type { AuthErrorCode } from "./auth-error-codes.js";

    export class AxonHttpError extends Error {
      constructor(
        public readonly status: number,
        public readonly code: AuthErrorCode | string,
        public readonly body: string,
      ) {
        super(`${status} ${code}: ${body}`);
        this.name = "AxonHttpError";
      }

      /** Narrow the code to AuthErrorCode if it matches a known variant. */
      isAuthError(): this is AxonHttpError & { code: AuthErrorCode } {
        return (AUTH_ERROR_CODES as readonly string[]).includes(this.code);
      }
    }

Keep AuthErrorCode | string as the type so unknown future codes don't break the SDK.

### 6. Export from index.ts

    export {
      AUTH_ERROR_CODES,
      AUTH_ERROR_STATUS,
      AUTH_ERROR_COUNT,
      type AuthErrorCode,
    } from "./auth-error-codes.js";

### L8 golden client contract — OUT OF SCOPE

The original bead asked for an L8 golden client test that round-trips all 14 (now 15) error codes against a live server. That requires spinning up an axon-server test fixture and sending 15 defective requests, then asserting the SDK surfaces the right variants. This is valuable but non-trivial — it needs a running server. DEFER to a follow-up bead once the full integration harness is stable.

For this bead, the parity test (which proves Rust and TS agree on the manifest) is sufficient.

